Although rigorous treatment with calculus is not required in the A-level syllabus, it is however useful for us to understand the physical significance of some of the calculus notations as they are commonly used to define physical quantities.

### The Derivative : \(\dfrac{d\psi}{dx}\)

Consider a graph of \(y\) vs. \(x\) as indicated by the curve in Figure 1. \(\dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}\) indicates the gradient of the line joining the 2 points A and B on the line.

Figure 2 shows that if we move point B closer towards point A, eventually the 2 points will meet. At this point gradient of the line AB will be exactly equal to the gradient of the tangent of the curve at A. (as represented by the bold straight line). Mathematically, we say:

\[\lim_{xx\to 0}\dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\dfrac{d\psi}{dx}=\text{gradient of the tangent of the $y-x$ graph}\]

This physical interpretation is very important in physics as many physical quantities are expressed in this derivative form.

For example, in our study of kinematics, we have :

Velocity, \(\nu\) = Rate of change of displacement with respect to time

\[=\dfrac{ds}{dt}\] \[=\text{Gradient of tangent of the $s$ -$ $t$ graph}\]

and

Acceleration, \(a\) = Rate of change of velocity with respect to time

\[=\dfrac{d\nu}{dt}\] \[=\text{Gradient of the tangent of the $\nu$ -$ $t$ graph}\]

Figure 2: Tangent of the curve at A.

### The Integral: \(\int y\ dx\)

The reverse process to taking the derivative is referred to either as _integration_ or finding the _anti-derivative_. Graphically, it is equivalent to finding the area under the curve. Let us see why.

Consider a \(y\)-\(x\) graph as shown in Figure 3. Suppose we wish to find the area under the graph from some initial \(x\) value, \(x_{\text{initial}}\) to some final \(x\) value, \(x_{\text{final}}\). One way to do so is break the area up into \(n\) number of small rectangles each of some area, \(A_{i}\).

Hence, the area of each small rectangle can be written as: \(A_{i}=y_{i}\Delta x\) and the total area under the curve can be estimated by summing the area of all these little rectangles, i.e.

\[\text{Total area, }A=\sum_{i=1}^{n}y_{i}\Delta x\]

where the symbol \(\sum\) (upper case Greek sigma) signifies a sum over all terms, i.e. over all values of \(i\).

For the approximation of the area to be even better, we can try to divide the area into smaller and smaller rectangles, by decrease the interval \(\Delta x\), i.e. we say that we let \(\Delta x\to 0\). Therefore,

\[A=\lim_{\Delta x\to 0}\sum_{i=1}^{n}y_{i}\Delta x\]

This is also written as \(\int\limits_{x_{\text{final}}}^{x_{\text{final}}}y(x)\ dx\). So, \(\int\limits_{x_{\text{final}}}^{x_{\text{final}}}y(x)\ dx\) is the area under the \(y\)-\(x\) graph.

Figure 3: Finding the area under a curve. The area of the shaded rectangle is equal to the product of the width of the rectangle \(\Delta x\) and the \(y\) value of the curve at the particular \(x\), \(y_{i}\).

We now use the defining equations for acceleration and velocity to illustrate the use of the above concept.

The defining equation for acceleration of an object is \(\ a=\frac{\mathrm{d}\nu}{dt}\)

Therefore, the change in velocity of an object is

\[\nu_{\text{traul}}-\nu_{\text{traul}}=\int_{t_{\text{traul}}}^{t_{\text{traul}}} \alpha(t)\ dt\]

which is the area under a-t graph.

Similarly, velocity of an object is \(\nu=\frac{ds}{dt}\)

Rearranging the equation, we also have the change in displacement of an object given as

\[s_{\text{traul}}-s_{\text{traul}}=\int_{t_{\text{traul}}}^{t_{\text{traul}}}\nu(t )\ dt\]

which is the area under \(\nu\)-t graph.

