A mass \(m\) attached to the end of a spiral spring exerts a downward force on it and stretches it by an amount \(e\) as shown in the diagram.

If the spring obeys Hooke's law, then the extension \(e\) is directly proportional to the extending tension, \(F_{\text{s}}\), i.e.,

\[F_{\text{s}} =-k\epsilon\text{\ \ where \ }k\text{\ is a constant.}\]

Since the mass is in equilibrium, the net force on it is zero (\(\sum F=0\)).

\[mg+(-k\epsilon) =0\] \[\Rightarrow mg =k\epsilon\]

Suppose the mass is now pulled down a further distance \(x\) below its equilibrium position, then the tension in the spring is increased to \(-k(\epsilon+x)\). Thus the resultant force on the mass is given by

\[F =mg-k(e+x)\] \[=k\epsilon-k(\epsilon+x)\] (since \[mg=k\epsilon\] ) \[=-k\alpha\]

i.e., the resultant force is acting upwards, with the direction opposite to that of the displacement.

By Newton's 2nd law,

\[ma =-k\alpha\] \[\Rightarrow a =-\frac{k}{m}x\]

Since \(k\) and \(m\) are fixed, the oscillation of a mass on spring is simple harmonic.

The angular frequency \(\omega\) is given by \(\omega^{2}=\frac{k}{m}\)

\[\Rightarrow T=\frac{2\pi}{\omega}=2\pi\sqrt{\frac{m}{k}}\]

