## Introduction to Thermal Physics

_Defining Our System_

When we are studying a physical phenomenon, the first thing we can do is to do some kind of 'isolation' i.e. we 'pluck' some part of that thing out from its surroundings. This 'plucked out' part is what we commonly call the'system'. The surface that separates the system from its surroundings is called the boundary. It is important to be strict about the boundary between the system and its surroundings i.e. we should not be sloppy or hazy when it comes to defining the system boundary at the outset of our study.

_Thermodynamics Properties of A System - Macroscopic vs Microscopic_

After we have defined our system, the next thing is of course to decide which aspect(s) of the system we wish to observe. In science, people are keen on those aspects that can be studied in the laboratory. Furthermore, we try to quantify such aspects i.e. ascribe numbers to them. In Thermodynamics, some of the aspects of the system we usually deal with are: length, volume, density, energy, pressure, temperature, mass etc. We call them properties or physical quantities of the system.

Such properties are separated into two categories: macroscopic and microscopic. Taking energy for example: macroscopic forms of energy are those in which a system possesses as a whole with respect to some outside reference frame, such as kinetic and potential energies of the centre-of-mass of the system. The microscopic forms of energy, on the other hand, are those related to the molecular structure of the system and the degree of molecular activity. They are independent of outside reference frames. The sum of all the microscopic forms of energy of a system is its _internal energy_.

_State of A System - A Set of Its Properties_

If a system is not undergoing any change, the set of all the properties of the system that can be measured or calculated will specify the condition of this system. We call this the _state_ of the system. At a given state, all the properties of a system have fixed values. If the value of even one property changes, the state will change to a different one. The state of a system is hence a condition of the system specified in terms of the totality of its properties.

