### Temperature Measurement & Temperature Scales

#### From an Empirical Scale1 to an Absolute Scale

Footnote 1: See Appendix B: Empirical Scale

_The Problem with the Empirical Scale_

Consider this scenario: two different thermometers working on different thermometric properties2 X and Y are calibrated on the same fixed points - melting ice and boiling water.

Say we assign the number 0 and 100 at these two fixed points for the two thermometers, so we have an empirical Centigrade Scale. Now, so long as the two thermometers measure the temperature of melting ice and boiling water we will get perfect agreement in temperature readout from these two thermometers but what if we use them to measure other temperatures? Clearly, the two different thermometric properties X and Y do not have to vary with temperature linearly and certainly not in the same way.

_Ideal Gas Scale_

This disagreement between thermometers using different thermometric properties is clearly a disadvantage of the empirical scale. One way of solving this is to take one scale as a standard in which all temperatures are expressed. This specially chosen standard scale must be independent of the thermometric property used hence such a scale is sometimes known as an **absolute scale**.

An ideal gas is one that follows the gas laws at all conditions of temperature and pressure. To do so, the gas needs to completely abide by the kinetic-molecular theory. There is no such thing as an ideal gas in real life. A real gas deviates most from an ideal gas at low temperatures and high pressures. Gases are most ideal at high temperature and low pressure. The figure below shows a graph of PV/RT plotted against pressure for 1 mol of a gas at three different temperatures of 200 K, 500 K, and 1000 K. The magnitude of the deviations from ideality is greatest for the gas at 200 K and least for the gas at 1000 K.

One way to minimize disagreement between thermometers is to use the gas under conditions when it behaves approximately like an ideal gas where the ideal gas equation of state (\(PV=nRT\)) holds. In this case, the volume of a fixed mass of gas \(V\) will be directly proportional to the absolute temperature \(T\) if the gas pressure \(P\) is kept constant. This relationship works for any gas under ideal conditions (hence independent of the type of gas) which in theory gives the most undisputed temperature measurement. Temperature measurement here is read in the Ideal Gas Scale.

The unit for this scale is kelvin. The symbol is K. The reference temperature (fixed point) is set at zero kelvin (0 K) - the _absolute zero_. This is a theoretical temperature as it has not been attained experimentally. How about another fixed point? The state in which ice, liquid water, and water vapour coexist in equilibrium - a state known as the triple point of water was chosen as this temperature can be accurately and reproducibly measured. It was assigned the value 273.16 K.

So the interval between the two fixed points is 273.16 K. If you remember the basic SI unit for temperature, does this strike a bell? The kelvin, unit of thermodynamic temperature, is the fraction 1/273.16 of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point of water.

#### Other Absolute Scales

The ideal gas scale represents a big advancement as it relies on the universal property of any gas under ideal behaviour (rather than on a particular gas). It is hence an absolute scale.

_Thermodynamic Scale_

Another absolute scale known is the _Thermodynamic Scale_. It is based on the theoretical efficiency of a perfectly reversible heat engine. This engine can work on any working fluid hence this is the foundation for an absolute scale (as opposed to an empirical scale).

The thermodynamic scale is equivalent to the ideal gas scale.

_Celsius Scale_

If the temperature of ice is 0\({}^{\circ}\) on the Centigrade Scale (most of us roughly have an idea how cold it is), then on the thermodynamic scale, it would be 273.15 K which is a totally unfamiliar number to most people. To make the numbers on the thermodynamic scale resemble those in the empirical scale more familiar to us, an arithmetical adjustment is made to it and the _Celsius Scale_ is created. Thus the Celsius Scale is actually a "displaced" Thermodynamic Scale made to look like the familiar Centigrade Scale. Note that Celsius is an absolute scale designed to produce the temperature readout like the (familiar) empirical Centigrade Scale.

To convert temperature measured in degree Celsius (_Celsius Scale_) to kelvin (_Thermodynamic Scale_):

T/K = f/oC + 273.15

