### Microscopic View of Energy

What type of changes will occur to a system when heat enters or leaves its boundary? To answer this question, we need to adopt a microscopic view of our system. The internal mechanism of a system is explained by the kinetic theory of matter - it states that all matter is made up of a large number of tiny atoms or molecules which are in continuous motion.

A neat way to present the molecular information of a system is to use the concept of energy - in this case, energy related to the molecules within the boundary of our system. At the molecular level, we are concerned primarily with two types of energy:

1. the kinetic energy due to the random movement of the molecules - microscopic kinetic energy, and
2. the potential energy among molecules due to the intermolecular forces between them - microscopic potential energy. Gases have zero potential energy (or close enough to zero for real gases and zero for ideal gases). In relation to this, solids and liquids have negative potential energy. When heat is supplied to a solid or liquid, potential energy increases, so the value of potential energy becomes less negative and gets closer to zero.

#### Internal Energy

Energy is a scalar quantity. If we sum up all the above two types of energy for all molecules within the boundary of our system, the result of this summation is known as the _internal energy_.

The internal energy \(U\) is the summation of microscopic kinetic energy due to random motion of the molecules and the microscopic potential energy due to intermolecular forces.

#### Microscopic Kinetic Energies

_Due to the random movement of molecules._

_The microscopic potential energies arise from intermolecular forces between the molecules_

_Average microscopic K.E. of the molecules_

_\(\propto\) Absolute temperature of the system._

Using this concept of internal energy and its associated concepts, we can explain the following:

1. At different phases, the molecules within the system exhibit different characteristics. The existence of three phases of matter is determined primarily by the intermolecular forces and the type of motion which the molecules will have because of their internal energy.
2. The temperature of a body is a measure of the _average kinetic energy_ of the molecules that make up the body. Increases in this microscopic kinetic energy of a body can be detected by a rise in its temperature. Increases in microscopic potential energy, on the other hand, does not result in any rise in temperature. This is most dramatically demonstrated by boiling water; despite all the heat being supplied, the reading on the thermometer remains constant.

