## 3 Ideal Gas

_Kinetic Theory_

The kinetic theory of matter states that all matter is made up of a large number of tiny atoms or molecules which are in continuous motion. We can explain the three phases of matter and their various macroscopic properties in terms of the behaviour of their constituent molecules (microscopic properties).

_Why Study Ideal Gases_

The study of the three phases of matter is not an easy task as it involves various branches of knowledge in physics like mechanics (whether classical or quantum) and statistics etc. Among the three phases of matter, the gaseous phase presents itself as the easiest one to be studied especially when the gas molecules are spaced far apart from each other and not interacting with each other. Hence we will attempt to explain some macroscopic properties of such a gas via the collective behaviour of the gas molecules. This simplified gas system is known as the **ideal gas** and it has the following microscopic properties:

_Assumptions/Properties of an Ideal Gas_

1. A gas consists of a very large number of molecules.
2. The gas molecules are moving randomly.
3. Collisions of the gas molecules with one another and with the walls of the container are perfectly elastic.
4. There are no intermolecular forces of attraction.
5. The volume of the gas molecules is negligible, compared to the volume of the container, which is the volume of the gas.
6. The duration of collisions is negligible, compared to the time interval between collisions.

_Ideal Gas Equation of State_

For an ideal gas, the equation of state is:

\[\begin{array}{l}pV=\ nRT\end{array}\]

which can be expressed as \(pV=\ NkT\), since \(R=\ kN_{A}\),

where

pressure \(p\), volume \(V\), absolute temperature \(T\), amount of ideal gas in moles \(n\), amount of ideal gas in number of molecules \(N\), molar gas constant \(R=8.31\) J K\({}^{-1}\) mol\({}^{-1}\) and Boltzmann constant \(k=1.38\) x \(10^{-23}\) J K\({}^{-1}\) are linked.

### A Really Huge Number - The Avogadro Number, \(N\)

