### Molecular Interpretation of Pressure

#### How Kinetic Theory Explains the Nature of Pressure Exerted by Gas

According to the kinetic theory, a gas confined in a container is made up of a large number of gas molecules moving randomly and colliding with each other as well as with the walls of the container.

When the gas molecules collide elastically with the container of the gas, they rebound off the wall with the same speed. Clearly, the walls of the container exert a force on the gas molecules to cause their momentum to change in direction. By Newton's 2\({}^{nd}\) Law, this force is equal to the rate of change of momentum of the molecule. By Newton's 3\({}^{rd}\) Law, the molecules exert an equal but opposite force on the walls.

Since there is a large number of molecules, the number of collisions at any instant is very large and practically constant, resulting in a constant gas pressure.

The **pressure by the gas on the container** is the **average force per unit area exerted by the molecules on the walls of the container.**

The pressure \(P\) due to the gas molecules on a wall of the container can be written as

\[P = \frac{\text{average force exerted on the wall by molecules}}{\text{area of the wall}}\] \[= \frac{\text{(no. of collisions per unit time)(change of momentum per collision)}}{\text{area of the wall}}\]

We can now explain how the following factors can lead to an increase in pressure of a gas:

* **No. of molecules in the container.** All other conditions being constant, a larger number of molecules will imply more collisions made with the wall of the container.
* **Volume of container.** Having a smaller container implies that the molecules need to travel less distance to reach the next wall after rebounding from the opposite wall. Therefore, the no. of collisions they make with the walls per unit time increases.
* **Mass of the molecule.** The type of gas used will determine the mass of a molecule which in turn determines the momentum that each molecule possesses. The larger the mass of a molecule, the greater the momentum it will have. Thus, the change of momentum of the molecules per collision will be greater.
* **Velocities of the molecules.** The momentum of each gas molecule is determined by its velocity. A molecule possessing a larger velocity will have a greater momentum and hence its change in momentum will correspondingly be larger per collision.

