Consider the component of velocity \(v_{I}\) along the positive \(y\)-axis. After colliding with the wall A, the molecule rebounds with a velocity \(-v_{I}\) since the collision is perfectly elastic.

\begin{tabular}{l l} Momentum before collision & = \(mv_{I}\) \\ Momentum after collision & = \(-mv_{1}\) \\ \(:\). change of momentum & = \(-mv_{1}\) -\(mv_{1}\) \\  & = \(-2mv_{1}\) \\ \end{tabular}

**Step 3 Find the average force on the wall due to the bombardment of molecules on the wall**

Assuming that the molecule does not collide with other molecules, the time interval \(t\) between a collision of the molecule with the wall A and its next collision with the same wall is the same as the time the molecule takes to move from wall A to wall B and back and is given by:

\[\Delta t=\frac{2L}{v_{1}}\]

Hence, the number of collisions made by the molecule with wall A per unit time \(=\frac{1}{\Delta t}=\frac{v_{1}}{2L}\)

the average force exerted on the molecule by wall A \(=\frac{\Delta(mv)}{\Delta t}=-2mv_{1}\times\frac{v_{1}}{2L}=-\frac{mv_{1}^{ \ 2}}{L}\)By Newton's 3\({}^{\text{rd}}\) Law, the force exerted on wall A by the molecule = \(\dfrac{mv_{1}^{2}}{L}\)

During its passage back and forth across the container, the molecule may collide with the top and bottom and sides of the container, but this does not alter its component of momentum and thus does not alter our result. It may also collide elastically with other molecules which may change its \(v_{l}\). However, any loss (or gain) of momentum is acquired by other molecules, and because we will eventually sum over all the molecules, this effect will be included. So our result above is not altered.

The actual force due to one molecule is a spike, but because a huge number of molecules are striking the wall per second, the force is, on average, nearly constant. To calculate the force due to all the molecules in the container, we have to add the contribution of each.

Since there are \(N\) molecules, each with the component of velocity along the \(y\)-axis as \(v_{1}\), \(v_{2}\), \(v_{3}\),..., \(v_{N}\) respectively, then the total force on wall A due to the collision of these \(N\) molecules is

\[F=\dfrac{mv_{1}^{2}}{L}+\dfrac{mv_{2}^{2}}{L}+\dfrac{mv_{3}^{2}}{L}+\dots+ \dfrac{mv_{N}^{2}}{L}\]

