## 4 State of A System

We started this topic by introducing the concept of a system. If a system is not undergoing any change, the set of all the properties that can be measured or calculated throughout the entire system will specify the condition of this system. We call this the state of the system.

For this course, there are a few properties of a system that we are interested in: pressure \(p\), volume \(V\), temperature \(T\), internal energy \(U\).

_pV Diagram_

One way to monitor how a system changes its state is to chart the properties on a diagram. One such diagram is known as an indicator diagram. We will use mainly the pressure vs volume graph (pV diagram). A point on the pV diagram indicates a particular state of the system.

_Process_

A process occurs when a system changes from one state to another state. In our course, we indicate a process using a line with an arrow that connects the initial state to the final state.

### First Law of Thermodynamics

The study of any system is centred on the concept of energy conservation. We will now develop this concept in the context of thermodynamics.

Here are the two forms of energy we have dealt with so far:

\begin{tabular}{l l}
1) & Heat transfer \(Q\) \\
2) & Internal energy \(U\) \\ \end{tabular} We have shown that if heat enters or leaves the boundary of a system, the internal energy could change.

So the first link between these two forms of energy could be: \(\Delta U\ =\ Q\)

A positive sign for \(Q\) means heat enters the system and the internal energy \(U\) increases (leading to a positive sign for \(\Delta U\)).

This link between \(\Delta U\) and \(Q\) may appear correct. However it is incomplete. Your experience would have told you that the internal energy could change even when there is no heat flow. Can you describe one?

There are certainly other forms of energy transfer (other than heat) that could affect the internal energy.

We use the term 'work' (symbol \(W\)) to represent these alternative energy transfers.

So our energy transformation relationship becomes: \(\Delta U\ =\ Q\ +\ W\)

This is known as the _First Law of Thermodynamics_:

The increase in the internal energy of a system is the sum of the heat supplied to the system and the work done on the system.

We will limit work \(W\) mainly to the energy transfer via some form of force or pressure.

Remember that in mechanics, if a force \(F\) acting on a system causes the point of application to move by a distance \(x\) in the direction of \(F\), we say that positive work \(Fx\) is done on the system. So there is an attempt by the agent exerting the force \(F\) to transfer energy of magnitude \(Fx\) into the system.

This can be applied to a gas system.

Suppose an external pressure \(P_{ext}\) is exerted on a gas and the gas is compressed by a tiny distance \(x\) at constant cross-sectional area \(A\). In this case, work done by external agent, \(W\ =\ +P_{ext}(Ax)\ =\ +P_{ext}V\).

One immediate advantage of using a \(\mathrm{pV}\) diagram is that it allows us to visualize the work done \(W\) on our system. The magnitude of \(W\) for any process is the area between the line due to this process and the volume axis. How about the sign of \(W\)? If the system contracts (volume decreases), \(W\) is positive and vice versa.

