_Isothermal Process (Constant Temperature Process)_

Imagine an ideal gas undergoing isothermal expansion at constant temperature \(T_{1}\) from state \(i\) to state \(f\).

\[pV\ =\ nRT_{1}\ \ \ \Rightarrow\ \ p\ =\ \ (nRT_{1})\left(\frac{1}{V}\right)\]

Plotting \(p\) against \(V\) gives a reciprocal graph.

We have already proven that the internal energy of an ideal gas is a function of its absolute temperature. Hence internal energy of an ideal gas remains constant during an isothermal process; i.e. \(\Delta U\ =\ 0\).

To maintain constant temperature throughout the process, the expansion or compression should be done in a good conductor, and very slowly, to allow for effective heat exchange with the surroundings and hence for temperature to stay constant.

By the first law of thermodynamics, \(Q\ =\ -W\)

