#### 12.5.1 Charges in Equilibrium on Conductors

An electrical conductor contains charges that are free to move. Hence, when a conductor is charged, the charges will always redistribute themselves until the excess charge resides on the surface (they try to move out of the conductor as they repel each other). When the charges are no longer moving about, i.e. they have settled down in equilibrium, they experience no net force. This implies that the electric field in the conductor is zero.

Since the charges at the surface experience no force parallel to the surface (else they will continue to move along the surface),

From \(F_{\neq}=qE_{\neq}=0\)

\(\Rightarrow\) **Electric field along the surface is zero, \(E_{\neq}=0\)**.

From \(E=-\dfrac{dV}{dr}\)

\(\Rightarrow\) \(\dfrac{dV}{dr}=0\) along the surface of the conductor

\(\Rightarrow\) **The surface of a conductor is an equipotential surface.**

\(\Rightarrow\) **Electric field lines emerging or ending on a conductor are perpendicular to the surface.**

Furthermore, since the electric field within a conductor is zero, there is no potential gradient within the conductor all the way to the surface

\(\Rightarrow\) **The potential in the conductor is constant everywhere inside the conductor and is equal to its value at the surface.**

\(\Rightarrow\) **No field lines exist within the conductor.**

