### Deriving the Potential Energy and the Potential of an Electric Field by a Point Charge

**[Adapted from: Duncan, 2000, p 204]**

Consider a point charge +\(Q\). To find the potential of the electric field at **A** a distance \(r\) away from +\(Q\), we bring a very small test charge +\(q_{o}\) from infinity to the point **A** (allowing for no gain in kinetic energy) and find the work done by the external force to carry out this action.

We note that when the test charge is moving in the field set up by the source, it experiences a varying electrical force \(F_{E}\). An external force needs to move it from infinity to the point.

Now, the work done _dW_ by the external force to move a small distance of _dx_ towards the source charge is

\[dW=F_{ext}dx\]

Since the test charge is moved at a constant velocity, \(F_{ext}\) = -\(F_{E}\). Therefore,

\[dW=-F_{E}dx\]

The electric force experienced by the test charge a distance \(x\) away from the source charge is

\(F_{E}=\dfrac{Qq_{o}}{4\pi\varepsilon_{o}x^{2}}\). Therefore, we have the work done by the external force,

\[W=-\overset{\prime}{\underset{\infty}{\int}}F_{E}dx=-\overset{\prime}{\underset {\infty}{\int}}\dfrac{Qq_{o}}{4\pi\varepsilon_{o}x^{2}}dx=-\dfrac{Qq_{o}}{4 \pi\varepsilon_{o}}[-\dfrac{1}{r}]=\dfrac{Qq_{o}}{4\pi\varepsilon_{o}r}\]

By definition of the electrical potential, the potential at point A is therefore,

\[V=\dfrac{W}{q_{o}}=\dfrac{Q}{4\pi\varepsilon_{o}r}\]

## Appendix B Deriving the Relationship between Force and Potential Energy

The relationship between a (conservative) force \(F\) and the associated potential energy is given by

\[F=-\frac{dU}{dx}\]

This is a general relationship that applies to all conservative forces, of which the gravitational force and the electric force are examples.

To get this relationship, it is best to look at a specific case. In this case we will look at the electrical force \(F_{E}\) experienced by a charge in an electrical field.

By conservation of (mechanical) energy, assuming that no dissipative forces act on the system,

Work done by an external force on the system \(W\) = Increase in P.E. + Increase in K.E. of system

Assuming we move the object in the field at a constant velocity

\(\Rightarrow\) Increase in K.E. of system = 0

Now, let us move the object (a small charge in this case) by a small distance of \(\hat{\alpha}\)x in the direction of the external force, the small amount of work done \(\hat{\alpha}W\) by the external force is this case can be written as

\[\hat{\alpha}W=F_{ext}\,\hat{\alpha}x\]

Since the object is moving with constant velocity, \(F_{ext}\) = -\(F_{E}\)

Hence, we have

\[\hat{\alpha}W=F_{ext}\,\hat{\alpha}x\]

\[\Rightarrow\qquad\hat{\alpha}W=\mbox{ - }F_{E}\,\hat{\alpha}x\]

Now, as stated above, the work done by the external force results in the gain of potential energy of the system, hence we have

\[\Rightarrow\qquad\hat{\alpha}U=\hat{\alpha}W=\mbox{ - }F_{E}\,\hat{\alpha}x\qquad\mbox{ where }U\mbox{ is the potential energy}\]

which can be written as

\[\Rightarrow\qquad F_{E}=-\frac{dU}{dx}\qquad\mbox{(derived)}\]

