## 13.7 Internal resistance of a source of e.m.f.

All practical sources of e.m.f. have internal resistance. The chemicals within a cell offer a resistance to current flow, known as the internal resistance of the cell.

### 13.7.1 Terminal potential difference, e.m.f and internal resistance

Consider a simple circuit with a cell of e.m.f. \(\mathcal{E}\) and a load of resistance \(R\). From the energy point of view, the cell is the supplier while the load is the consumer of electrical energy. However, the cell has internal resistance which would consume part of the energy. Hence, less energy is available to drive each coulomb round the external circuit.

A cell can be represented as an ideal source of e.m.f. in series with a resistor representing the internal resistance of the cell. This internal resistance _cannot be_ separated out or measured directly.

By the law of conservation of energy,

Energy supplied by the e.m.f. = total energy consumed by the load and internal resistance of the cell

Since energy is supplied continuously, it follows that:

Power supplied by the e.m.f. = total power consumed by the load and internal resistance of the cell

\[P_{\mathit{eff}}=P_{\mathit{load}}+P_{\mathit{loss}}\] \[I\mathcal{E}=IV_{R}+IV_{r}\] \[I\mathcal{E}=IV_{R}+I^{2}r\] \[\mathcal{E}=V_{R}+Ir\] \[V_{R}=\mathcal{E}-Ir\]

Thus, the _potential difference across the terminals of a cell_ (_terminal p.d._) of a source supplying current to an external circuit is always _smaller than its e.m.f._ due to the presence of the internal resistance, \(r\).

If the circuit is open, no current will flow through the circuit and the terminal p.d. of the source will be equal to the e.m.f. of the source.

The output efficiency of the above circuit is given by:

\[\mathit{Efficiency}=\frac{\text{useful power output}}{\text{power input}}\] \[\mathit{Efficiency}=\frac{P_{\mathit{load}}}{P_{\mathit{off}}} =\frac{I^{2}R}{IE}=\frac{IR}{E}=\frac{\left(\frac{E}{R+r}\right)R}{E}=\frac{ R}{R+r}\]

