### Magnetic Force on a Moving Electric Charge

If we look into the microscopic view of the charges moving in a magnetic field, an expression for the magnitude of the force acting on a charge \(Q\) moving with velocity \(\mathbf{v}\) in a magnetic field of flux density \(B\) is given by

\[F_{B}=B_{\perp}Q\mathbf{v}\]

where \(B_{\perp}\)is the component of the magnetic flux density perpendicular to the velocity of the moving charges.

Note:

1. The magnetic force is maximum when the charge is moving perpendicularly to the magnetic field.
2. A charge in a magnetic field does not experience any force when

* it is moving parallel to the direction of the magnetic field,
* it is stationary in the field.
3. If the direction of the magnetic flux density and the velocity of the charged particles are perpendicular, the direction of the magnetic force on a charge moving in a magnetic field can be determined using Fleming's Left Hand Rule. By convention, the direction of conventional current is given by the direction of flow of positive charges.

