### Motion of a Charged Particle in a Uniform Magnetic Field

Let's now look at how moving charges that are not confined within a wire are affected by a magnetic field. We will again use Fleming's Left-Hand Rule to find the direction of this force.

Consider a positively charged particle moving at velocity \(v\) in a uniform magnetic field \(B\).

Figure 14.8.1 Charge moving at a velocity \(v\) in a uniform magnetic field

Using Fleming's Left Hand Rule, and the concept that the direction of the convention current is the direction of motion of the positively charged particle, we can deduce that the direction of the magnetic force acting on the charged particle at this instant is upwards within the plane of the plane. This causes the particle to be deflected from its initial path.

However, the direction of the force remains perpendicular to the directions of both velocity and magnetic field (Fleming's Left Hand Rule) even as the charged particle deflects, hence the charged particle will move in a circular path! The **magnetic force acting on the moving charge provides the centripetal force** for it to move in a circular path.

The magnetic force on the positive charge provides the centripetal force:

\[Bqv=\frac{mv^{2}}{r}\,\]

where r is the radius of the circular path

\[r=\frac{mv}{Bq}\]

From this equation for the radius of the path, we can deduce that for particles entering the magnetic field with the **same velocity**, the **radius would be proportional to the mass-to-charge ratio** of the particle (i.e. \(\frac{m}{q}\)). The ratio of the charge on a particle to the mass of the particle (i.e. \(\frac{q}{m}\)) is known as the _specific charge_.

If \(T\) is the time taken to complete one revolution of the circular path and \(v\) is the constant speed of the charge,

\[v=r\omega\] \[v=r\frac{2\pi}{T}\] \[v= \left(\frac{mv}{Bq}\right)\frac{2\pi}{T}\] \[T=\frac{2\pi m}{Bq}\]

The **period _T_** is dependent on the mass, the magnetic flux density, and the charge of the particle. It is independent of the speed of the particle or the radius of the circular path.

