The electricity supply generated for consumers' use is a sinusoidal AC.

The time-variation of a sinusoidal current or voltage can be represented by the equation

\[x=\pm x_{0}\sin\omega t\quad\quad\text{or}\quad\quad x=\pm x_{0}\cos\omega t\]

where \(x_{0}=\text{peak (or maximum) value}\)

\(\omega=\text{angular frequency of the supply (rad s^{-1})}\).

Note that \(\omega=2\pi\ f\) where \(f\) is the frequency of the supply in hertz (Hz). Frequency is also related to the period \(T\) through the expression \(f=\dfrac{1}{T}\).

