### What does the root-mean-square (r.m.s.) value mean?

If a _steady DC_ passes through a resistive load \(R\), the power \(P\) dissipated can be calculated by \(P=VI\), \(P=I^{2}R\), or \(P=\dfrac{V^{2}}{R}\). Since \(V\) and \(I\) are unchanging for a DC, there is no difference between instantaneous and average power dissipated in the resistive load.

If the current through the load is _alternating current (AC)_, the **instantaneous power** dissipated must be changing with time, since \(V\) and \(I\) are changing with time. In practice, we are often only interested in the **average power** dissipation. Interestingly, the average power can be calculated by the same set of equations (\(P=VI\), \(P=I^{2}R\) or \(P=\dfrac{V^{2}}{R}\)), as long as we use the **root-mean-square** values \(V_{mn.}\) and \(I_{mn.}\).

So, what is the root-mean-square value then?

Suppose a periodic alternating current \(I\) passes through an electrical load of resistance \(R\), its instantaneous power \(P\) dissipated will be changing with time \(t\). The peak current is \(I_{0}\).

Instantaneous power \(P=VI=I^{2}R=\dfrac{V^{2}}{R}\)

Peak power \(P_{0}=V_{0}I_{0}=I_{0}^{2}R=\dfrac{V_{0}^{2}}{R}\)

In general,

mean power \(<P>=<I^{2}R>\)

\(=<I^{2}>R\) (since \(R\) is constant)

where \(<I^{2}>\) is the mean-squared current \(I\).

We define the root-mean-squared current \(I_{rms}=\sqrt{<I^{2}>}\),

then the mean power can also be expressed as \(<P>=(I_{rms})^{2}R\)

The **root-mean-square** value of an alternating current is that **equivalent constant direct current** that will **dissipate the same average power in a given resistive load**.

In other words, a direct current of 1 A and an alternating current of r.m.s. value of 1 A have **the same heating effect**, i.e. both currents dissipate the same power in a given resistor.

Mean power \(<P>=V_{rms}I_{rms}=I_{rms}^{2}R=\dfrac{V_{rms}^{2}}{R}\) [1]

Based on the above equation in [1], we can derive that \(\dfrac{V_{rms}=I_{rms}R}{R}\)

Note that the above relationships are not restricted to sinusoidal AC. They are applicable to non-sinusoidal AC as well.

Last but not least, for a periodic current with period \(T\), the mean-squared current \(<I^{2}>\) is computed using

\[<I^{2}>\ =\dfrac{\int\limits_{0}^{T}I^{2}\ dt}{T}=\dfrac{1}{T}\int\limits_{0}^{ T}I^{2}\ dt\.\]

In the next section, you will learn how to compute the r.m.s. values and the mean power for a sinusoidal AC.

