### Transformer

The transformer is a device which makes use of electromagnetic induction to produce a large alternating e.m.f. from a small one, or a small alternating e.m.f. from a large one. The primary and secondary coils are formed by winding insulated wires on a soft iron core, either one on top of the other or on separate limbs (as shown in the figures below). There is no electrical connection between the coils but they are linked magnetically via the soft iron core; i.e. the flux is the same in both coils.

Below are circuit symbols of transformers.

#### 16.4.1 Induced e.m.f.s in a transformer

When an alternating e.m.f. \(V_{p}\) is applied to the primary coil, alternating currents in both primary coil and secondary coil set up a resultant alternating flux \(\dot{\phi}\) in the core.

If \(N_{p}\) and \(N_{s}\) are the number of turns in the primary and secondary coils, their linkages with the flux \(\phi\) are

\[(\mathcal{O}_{\text{\tiny{infkagap}}})_{p}=N_{p}\,\phi\qquad\qquad\text{ and }\qquad\qquad(\mathcal{O}_{\text{\tiny{infkagap}}})_{s}=N_{s}\,\phi\]

The alternating flux induces an alternating e.m.f. \(E_{p}\) in the primary coil as well as an alternating e.m.f. \(E_{s}\) in the secondary coil. By Faraday's law, the magnitudes of \(E_{p}\) and \(E_{s}\) are given by

\[E_{p}=\frac{d(\mathcal{O}_{\text{\tiny{infkagap}}})_{p}}{dt}=N_{p}\,\frac{d \phi}{dt}\qquad\qquad\text{and }\qquad\qquad E_{s}=\frac{d(\mathcal{O}_{\text{\tiny{infkagap}}})_{s}}{dt}=N_{ s}\,\frac{d\phi}{dt}\]

Dividing the above two equations, we have

\[\frac{\text{e.m.f.\,induced in secondary}}{\text{e.m.f.\,induced in primary}}=\frac{E_{s}}{E_{p}}=\frac{N_{s}}{N_{p}}\]

Thus the transformer steps voltage up or down according to its 'turns-ratio' \(\frac{N_{s}}{N_{p}}\).

If \(V_{s}\) is the output p.d. across the secondary coil, then for an _ideal transformer_ that has _zero-resistance coils_. \(V_{p}=E_{p}\quad\text{and}\quad V_{s}=E_{s}\), giving

\[\frac{V_{s}}{V_{p}}=\frac{N_{s}}{N_{p}}\]

**Note that**

1. When the secondary coil is open-circuited, the same analysis can still be applied and resultant alternating flux \(\phi\) in the core will be due to the current in the primary coil.
2. \(V_{p}\) must be an alternating e.m.f.. If not, the flux in the primary coil would not change (except for a short time immediately after the e.m.f. is first applied) and there would be no induced e.m.f. in the secondary coil.
3. The induced e.m.f. \(E_{s}\) has the same frequency as the applied voltage \(V_{p}\).
4. If \(N_{s}>N_{p}\), the transformer is called a _step-up transformer_ because \(V_{s}>V_{p}\). A step-down transformer has \(N_{s}<N_{p}\).

#### 16.4.2 Power transmission in a transformer

If the transformer is ideal, i.e. _100% efficient_,

\[\textbf{output power}=\textbf{input power}\]

\[V_{s}I_{s}=V_{p}I_{p}\]

Thus, turns ratio \(\begin{array}{c}\framebox{$N_{s}=\frac{V_{s}}{N_{p}}=\frac{I_{p}}{V_{p}}= \frac{I_{p}}{I_{s}}$}\\ \end{array}\)

The above relationship is _only applicable to an ideal transformer_. In the A levels, transformers are assumed to be ideal unless otherwise stated.

Note that the relationship is obtained from the Principle of Conservation of Energy.

