### Atomic Structure and Line Spectra

#### Bohr's Model of Atomic Quantization

Rutherford's Planetary Model of Atom and its Flaws

Throughout mankind's history, the quest to understand the composition of matter and the structure of the atom has evolved through various theories3. By the 20th century, Ernest Rutherford's nuclear model was the most successful of all the various proposals.

Footnote 3: Around 500 BC, Democritus proposed the concept of atoms, suggesting that matter consists of indivisible particles. Later, Joseph John Thomson introduced the plum-pudding model, envisioning electrons embedded within a positively charged mass. This model was challenged by the gold-foil experiment conducted by Geiger and Marsden, leading Ernest Rutherford to propose a new planetary model featuring a dense, positively charged nucleus surrounded by orbiting electrons, akin to a miniature solar system. We will learn more about J1 Thomsons plumbuding model and Rutherfords planetary model of atoms in our study of Nuclear Physics.

In Rutherford's model of atom, the atom was made up of a massive, positive central nucleus, with electrons orbiting around this nucleus. However, although this model provided crucial insights into the atomic structure of the atom, it also faced significant flaws.

According to Maxwell's classical theory of electromagnetism, any accelerating electrical charge radiates electromagnetic waves. An electron orbiting in an atom would always have a centripetal acceleration and so should always be emitting electromagnetic radiation. With the electron continuously losing energy, the radius of the orbit should decrease continuously, and the electron should spiral into the nucleus with a fraction of a second. (Fig. 9.2)

Furthermore, in the 1800s, Michael Faraday had conducted a series of experiments and observed that atoms emit (and absorbs) only certain frequencies of electromagnetic radiation that were characteristics of the element - producing discrete line spectra. (Fig. 10)

According to classical theory, the _frequency_ of the electromagnetic waves emitted by the orbing electrons is equal to the frequency of revolution. As the electron spiral towards the nucleus, its frequency of revolution continuously increases and hence should emit a _continuous_ spectrum (a continuous variation of all frequencies). Classical theory, hence, could not explain the line spectrum emitted or absorbed by atoms.

