### Application of Bohr's Model to the Hydrogen Atom

The simplest Bohr model would be that of the hydrogen atom, which consists of just one electron and one proton. Bohr was able to derive the energy levels \(E_{n}\) for the hydrogen atom5:

Footnote 5: You are not required to memorise this formula or know how Bohr arrived at it. In fact, you are not required to know the energy levels or spectra for any particular element.

\[E_{n}=-\frac{13.6}{n^{2}}\;\;\mathrm{eV}\]

where \(n\) is known as the principal quantum number and is a positive integer (i.e., 1, 2, 3,...).

The electron normally occupies the energy level corresponding to \(n=1\), also known as the **ground state**,** At the **ground state**, the **electron has the lowest energy**, -13.6 eV, and orbits nearest to the proton (hydrogen nucleus).

The higher energy levels are called **excited states**. Fig. 12 shows how the energies of the excited states come closer and closer together as \(n\) increases.

The electron in a hydrogen atom at room temperature spends most of its time in the ground state. To raise the electron from the ground state (\(n=1\)) to the highest possible excited state (\(n=\infty\)), 13.6 eV of energy must be supplied. Supplying this amount of energy removes the electron from the atom, producing the positive hydrogen ion H\({}^{+}\). 13.6 eV is known as the **ionisation energy** of the hydrogen atom.

