#### Explanation of X-ray Emission Spectra

Two distinct processes are involved in X-ray emission (corresponding to the two distinct features of the X-ray spectrum in Fig. 17). The first process accounts for the bremsstrahlung, while the second accounts for the characteristic lines.

BremsstrahlungIn the first process, some of the electrons pass through the electric field of the atomic nuclei in the metal target. As a result of the interaction with the atomic nuclei, part or all of the kinetic energy of these electrons is converted directly to a **continuous spectrum** of photons, including X-rays. The electrons are slowed down or stopped by the target as a result. Because the electrons are slowed down in the process, this radiation is known as _bremsstrahlung_ (German word for 'braking radiation'.)

The intensity of the continuous background radiation decreases gradually for increasing wavelength, but is cut off sharply at the other end of the spectrum with a minimum wavelength \(\lambda_{min}\).

Cutoff Wavelength, \(\lambda_{min}\)Using the quantum theory of light, one can explain the existence of \(\lambda_{min}\) (which is often known as the _cutoff wavelength_).

When the bombarding electrons interact with the metal atoms in the target, they can lose any fraction of their initial energy, up to the maximum in a single interaction. If the electron loses all its energy in a single interaction, based on quantum theory, a single quantum of electromagnetic radiation (photon) is produced with maximum energy, and hence **minimum wavelength** (and **highest frequency**).

If the accelerating voltage of the X-ray tube is \(V\), and an electron has charge -\(e\), the electron gains kinetic energy \(eV\). Since, the most energetic photons are produced when this entire electron's kinetic energy is converted into a single photon, then, by conservation of energy,

Energy of photon emitted = Kinetic energy of the electron \(\implies\hbar\frac{c}{\lambda_{min}}=eV\)

Hence, the **cutoff wavelength \(\lambda_{min}\)**:**

\(\lambda_{min}=\frac{hc}{eV}\)

(for an electron completely stopped in its first interaction with the metal target)

From, the derivation, we can also see that the minimum wavelength \(\lambda_{min}\) in the bremsstrahlung process is _independent_ of the target material. It only depends on the accelerating voltage.

### The Characteristic Lines

The second process accounts for the peaks in the X-ray spectrum at certain frequencies (i.e., the characteristic X-rays in Fig. 17).

Electrons in atoms are grouped in various energy states called "shells." The shell nearest to the nucleus is known as the K shell. This is followed by the L shell, the M shell, the N shell and so on. (Fig 18 (a),(b))

In the X-ray tube, highly energetic electrons which have been accelerated by tens to hundreds of kilovolts of potential difference bombard the metal target. These highly energetic bombarding electrons can eject electrons from the _inner shells_ (i.e., closer to the nucleus) of the atoms of the metal target. The vacancies created will be quickly filled by electrons dropping down from higher levels, emitting X-rays with sharply defined frequencies associated with the difference between the atomic energy levels of the target atoms.

If \(E\) is the difference in energy between the two shells where the electron transition occurs, the frequency \(f\) of the radiation emitted is related to \(E\) by

\[E=hf.\]

As \(E\) is very high for electronic transitions between the K, L and M shells, the frequency \(f\) of the emitted radiation is also very high and the wavelength correspondingly short, typically of the order of \(10^{-9}\) m or less (i.e., in the X-ray region of the electromagnetic spectrum).

