#### Introduction

We have seen evidence that light can behave like a particle. But can Einstein's particulate theory of light explain the interference and diffraction of light? Unfortunately, it cannot. Such behaviour can only be explained using the wave theory of light. Hence, light also exhibits wave-like properties like diffraction, interference and polarization. (Experiments like Young's double-slit experiment clearly demonstrate this wave behavior.)

Therefore:

\[\boxed{Light\text{behaves}\textbf{both}\text{as particles and as a wave.}}\]

In fact, the equation \(E=hf\) contains this contradictory nature of light. The energy of a photon - a _particle_ of light - depends on the _frequency_ of the light. Light can have a frequency only if it is a wave.

#### De Broglie's Hypothesis - Matter Waves

As a graduate student in 1923, Louis de Broglie made an astounding suggestion. Since light can exhibit particle-like behaviour, then the converse should be true. Particles (like electrons) should also exhibit wave-like behaviour.

**De-Broglie Relationship:**

De Broglie boldly proposed that a relationship between momentum (of the particle) and wavelength (of the **associated matter wave**) exists for **all particles**:

\[\lambda=\frac{h}{p}\text{ where }p\text{ is the momentum of the particle}\]

\(\lambda\) is known as the _de Broglie wavelength_ of the particle.

