### 18.2 Rutherford's Alpha-Particle Scattering Experiment

Mini Lecture 1.1 - Rutherford's Alpha-Particle Scattering Experiment, [https://for.edu.sg/bvocd](https://for.edu.sg/bvocd).

_Hans Geiger_ and _Ernest Marsden_ carried out a series of experiments under the direction of _Ernest Rutherford_ in 1908-1913 at the _University of Manchester_ in England, where they shot helium nuclei at a thin layer of gold foil. The results of the experiments disproved Thomson's plum pudding model.

### 18.2.1 Details of Rutherford's Experiment

\(\circ\)**Aim:** To probe the internal structure of the atom.

\(\circ\)**Description**

In Rutherford's alpha(\(\alpha\))-particle scattering experiment, \(\alpha\)-particles (helium-4 nuclei) from a radioactive source were directed towards a sheet of gold foil in a vacuum chamber.

\(\bullet\)The _vacuum_ is necessary because alpha particles only have a short range of about 5 cm in air.

\(\bullet\)The gold foil, being very ductile, is rolled into a very thin sheet of 0.00004 cm (about 100 atoms) thick, so that the high-energy alpha particles can pass through it, instead of being absorbed by it.

\(\bullet\)The angular deflection of alpha particles is measured using a microscope that has a glass screen coated with zinc sulphide (Fig. 3). A charged particle impacting with the screen will produce a tiny flash of light, called a **scintillation**.

\(\circ\)To determine how the alpha particles are scattered, the number of scintillations \(N\) is obtained for each angular deflection \(\theta\). Fig. 4 shows the results of the alpha-particle scattering experiment. Note that the vertical axis is marked in powers of 10. If a linear scale were used, no deflections over angles larger than 10 or 20 degrees would be visible, and the relevant fact that about 1 in 8000 alpha particles are backscattered would be lost.

\(\circ\)**Predicted Alpha Scattering Based on Thomson's Model (Hypothesis)**

The positive charge and the negative electrons are distributed throughout the whole atom. Hence, the electric field inside the atoms should be quite small.

\(\bullet\)Alpha particles are doubly charged helium ions. As the electrical force on an \(\alpha\)-particle that enters the atoms should be quite weak, the maximum deflection \(\theta\) observed should at most be only a few degrees.

\(\circ\)**Actual Observation**

_More than 99% of \(\alpha\)-particles passed through with little or no angular deflection._

_A few \(\alpha\)-particles (~1 in 8000) backscattered, i.e., suffered deflections of more than 90\({}^{\circ}\). A very small number were even deflected backwards._

These results were so unexpected that Rutherford later wrote:

\({}^{\ast}\)_It was quite the most incredible event that ever happened to me in my life. It was almost as incredible as if you had fired a 15-inch shell at a piece of tissue paper and it came back and hit you."_

Figure 4: Graph showing the results of the \(\alpha\)-particle scattering experiment. Note that the vertical axis is marked in powers of 10.

Figure 3: Set up of Rutherfords Scattering Experiment.

Fig. 5 shows how alpha particles are scattered, depending on how close they pass the nucleus of a gold atom. **1**: Alpha particles that pass outside the gold atom altogether will experience it as an uncharged sphere and are not deflected at all. **2**: Alpha particles that pass through a gold atom's electron cloud experience a net positive charge and are deflected by the repulsive Coulomb force. **3**: The closer the alpha particle passes the nucleus, the greater the angle of deflection. **4**: About 1 in 8000 alpha particles hit a gold nucleus almost face-on, with the result that they are backscattered, i.e., scattered over angles larger than 90 degrees. About 1 in a million even get reflected in almost the same direction as where they came from.

