#### 18.5.4 Mass Defect

Recall that _mass_ and _energy_ are equivalent and are related by Einstein's equation \(E=mc^{2}\).

Since energy is released when the individual protons and neutrons bind to form a stable or semi-stable nucleus, **the nucleus will have a smaller mass than the total mass of the separate neutrons and protons.**

This difference in mass \(\Delta m\) is known as the _mass defect._

To calculate the mass defect \(\Delta m\) for a _nucleus_ that has \(Z\) protons and \(N\) neutrons:

\(\Delta m\) = (_Sum of mass of constituent nucleons_) - (_Mass of nucleus_)

\(\Delta m\) = (\(Zm_{p}+Nm_{n}\)) - (\(M_{nucleus}\))

where \(m_{p}\) is the mass of a proton, \(m_{n}\) is the mass of a neutron and \(M_{nucleus}\) is the mass of the nucleus.

It therefore follows from Einstein's mass-energy-equivalence relationship that:

\(\Delta m\) is the mass defect.

