#### Alpha Decay

\(\circ\) An \(\alpha\)-particle is the nucleus of a helium-4 (\({}^{4}_{2}\)He ) atom, with a charge of +2e. It may be emitted from an unstable nucleus.

\(\circ\) Alpha decay occurs when an unstable heavy nucleus (the "parent") ejects an alpha particle, transforming itself into a different nuclide (the "daughter") after losing two protons and two neutrons (Fig. 14).

\(\circ\) Alpha decay can be written symbolically as: \({}^{A}_{Z}\)X \(\rightarrow\)\({}^{A-4}_{Z-2}\)Y \(+\)\({}^{4}_{2}\)He where \({}^{A}_{Z}\)X is known as the **parent nucleus** and \({}^{A-4}_{Z-2}\)Y is known as the **daughter nucleus**, e.g. \({}^{238}\)U is an alpha emitter and decays according to the scheme \({}^{238}_{92}\)U \(\rightarrow\)\({}^{234}_{90}\)Th \(+\)\({}^{4}_{2}\)He (Fig. 14).

