### Decay Constant

Although radioactive decay is a random process, if the _number of radioactive nuclei is large_, we can associate a probability of decay to the nuclei.

\(\circ\)The rate at which a particular decay process occurs in a sample is proportional to the number of radioactive nuclei present:

\[\frac{dN}{dt}=-\lambda N\ \........................\ (1)\]

where \(\lambda\) is the proportionality constant known as the **decay constant**.

Note:

1. Since Activity \(A=-\frac{dN}{dt}\), we can also write equation (1) as \[\boxed{A=\lambda N}\ \........................\ (2)\]
2. Equation (1) can also be written as: \(\lambda=\frac{(-\frac{dN}{dt})}{N}\)

The _decay constant_ is the probability per unit time that a nucleus will decay.

3. Rewriting equation (1), we can also have: \[\frac{dN}{N}=-\lambda dt\] Integrating, \(\int_{N_{o}}^{N}\frac{1}{N^{\prime}}dN^{\prime}=-\lambda\int_{0}^{t}dt^{\prime}\) \[\Rightarrow \ln(\frac{N}{N_{o}})=-\lambda t\] \[\Rightarrow \boxed{N=N_{o}\,e^{-\lambda t}}........................\ (3)\] where \(N\) is the number of radioactive nuclei present at time \(t\) and \(N_{o}\) represents the number of undecayed radioactive nuclei at \(t=0\).

Equation (3) shows that _the number of undecayed radioactive nuclei in a sample decreases exponentially with time_ (Fig. 21).

