Each ionising particle or radiation produces a pulse voltage in the external circuit of a GM detector. In order to measure the number of pulses from the detectors, some form of counter must be used (Fig. 27). A scaler counts the actual number of pulses while a ratemeter gives directly the average number of pulses per second or _count rate_.

### _Scintillator_

Gas-filled detectors like the GM tube are inefficient as gamma detectors as the probability of an interaction is low. A scintillator is a "solid" detector which addresses this shortfall. The incoming ionising radiation interacts with the scintillator to produce many electronic transitions. The decay of these transitions produces many photons of low energy, i.e., the scintillator material _fluoresces_.

Each emitted photon travels through the transparent scintillator material and ejects an electron from a photosensitive surface. Each of these electrons goes on to emit more secondary electrons: the numbers of electrons are multiplied by a photomultiplier and turn into a voltage pulse. The pulse amplitude is a measure of the energy of the incident ionising radiation.

