## Appendix B Background Radiation

Background radiation is the ionising radiation that is constantly present in the environment. Sources of such radiation can be natural or man-made (Fig. 29).

### Natural Sources of Radiation

Naturally occurring radiation accounts for about 80% of our exposure. Most of the exposure is from indoor radon, followed by radiation from outer space and from the Earth's crust.

\(\circ\) **Radon**

Approximately 55% of our exposure to radiation comes from radon, which is a _colourless_, _odourless_ and _relatively inert_, naturally occurring radioactive gas. Radon-222 is one of the elements in the long radioactive decay chain from uranium-238 (Fig. 30) and the less common isotope radon-220 is part of the decay series from thorium-232 (Fig. 31), both of which can be found in rocks and soil.

\(\bullet\) **Dangers of Radon Gas**

Radon is the second leading cause of lung cancer in the United States, with only smoking causing more lung-cancer deaths. Key dangers associated with radon gas are not so much the radon itself, but its radioactive daughters, which are solid particles that easily attach themselves to dust particles, which may be inhaled. When inhaled, these particles stick to the surfaces of the bronchial tubes and the \(\alpha\)-particle emitted in the decay of the radon daughters damage the cells they are attached to, causing cancer.

\(\bullet\) **How Does Radon Get Into Homes?**

Radon usually migrates into homes and other buildings from the ground through openings in the floor or wall. Buildings trap radon inside, where it accumulates and may become a health hazard. Any home or building may have a radon problem, be it a new or an old home, a well-sealed or a draughty one, as well as homes with and without basements.

\(\circ\) **Soil and Buildings**

Natural radioactive material in rocks and soil account for about another 8% of the radiation dose a person typically receives in a year. The earth's crust contains small amounts of uranium, thorium and radium, as well as radioactive isotopes of several elements, including potassium. The radiation dose also comes from some building materials (such as bricks and concrete).

